  "meta": {
    "title": "MESS — risk of recurrence after a first seizure (Part 1)",
    "doi": "10.1016/S1474-4422(06)70383-0",
    "cff_info": "<h3>Risk of recurrence after a first seizure (Part 1)</h3><p>Estimates the chance of a further seizure within the next 12 months (COSY) after a first unprovoked seizure, from the MRC MESS trial, and the seizure-free interval after which the annual risk falls below 20% (a Group 1 / private-driving orientation cut-off used in some jurisdictions).</p><h3>Variables</h3><ul><li><strong>Aetiology</strong> — symptomatic (linked to a past neurological condition) vs cryptogenic/idiopathic (no identifiable cause).</li><li><strong>Treatment</strong> — immediate vs delayed antiepileptic-drug treatment.</li><li><strong>EEG</strong> and <strong>CT/MRI</strong> — normal, abnormal, or not done.</li><li><strong>Epilepsy in a first-degree relative</strong> and <strong>seizures only while asleep</strong>.</li><li><strong>Months seizure-free</strong> — COSY is reported at 6 and 12 months.</li></ul>",
    "authors": "Kim LG, Johnson TL, Marson AG, et al.",
    "journal": "The Lancet Neurology",
    "year": 2006,
    "outcome": "Prediction of risk of seizure recurrence after a single seizure and early epilepsy: further results from the MESS trial"
  },
  "thresholds": {
    "group1": 20,
    "group2": 2
  },
  "predictors": [
